-- Datatec, Firestone, Sovereign Foods May Move: South African Stocks Preview
-- B y   G a r t h   T h e u n i s s e n   a n d   N i c k y   S m i t h
-- 2010-09-21T06:26:11Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-09-21/datatec-firestone-sovereign-foods-may-move-south-african-stocks-preview.html
The following is a list of
companies whose shares may have unusual price changes in  South
Africa . Stock symbols are in parentheses after company names and
prices are from the last close.  South Africa’s  FTSE/JSE Africa All Share Index  increased
for the first time in four days, rising 297.37, or 1.1 percent,
to 28,710.93 at the close in Johannesburg.  AngloGold Ashanti Ltd. (ANG SJ): The price of gold for
immediate delivery touched a record of $1,285 an ounce
yesterday. The U.S.’s Federal Open Market Committee meets today
to discuss that country’s economic recovery. AngloGold shed 1.01
rand, or 0.3 percent, to 315.99 rand.  Gold Fields Ltd.  (GFI SJ)
added 53 cents, or 0.5 percent, to 107.12 rand.  BHP Billiton Plc.  (BIL SJ): The world’s largest mining
company has extended the deadline for its $40 billion bid for
Potash Corp. of Saskatchewan Inc. to Nov. 18. BHP Billiton’s
Chief Executive Officer Marius Kloppers will meet Canada’s
lawmakers today to discuss the transaction. The stock added 52
cents, or 0.2 percent, to 219.12 rand.  Cashbuild Ltd.  (CSB SJ): The building materials retailer
will return about 50 million rand ($7 million) to the
beneficiaries of trust it created in 2005 for a share sale to
black investors after the value of its shares increased. The
stock was unchanged at 72.80 rand.  Datatec Ltd.  (DTC SJ): The computer-services company said it
has agreed to buy the business of Touchbase Singapore from
Touchbase Group. The Johannesburg-based company’s stock rose 19
cents, or 0.6 percent, to 34.09 rand.  Firestone Energy Ltd.  (FSE SJ): The coal-exploration company
said it posted a basic loss of 16 cents per share in the year to
end-June, compared with a loss of 12 cents per share the
previous year, according to a stock exchange filing. Firestone’s
stock fell 1 cent, or 3.7 percent, to 26 cents.  Litha Healthcare Group Ltd.  (LHG SJ): The South African
healthcare company said first-half net income rose to 17.5
million rand from 14.2 million. The shares rose 1 cents, or 0.9
percent, to 1.16 rand.  Pioneer Foods Ltd.  (PFG SJ): A South African food company
appears in the Competition Appeal Court today over a fine
imposed by the country’s antitrust regulators for price-fixing,
Business Day newspaper reported. The Competition Commission will
ask the court to increase the size of the 195.7 million rand
fine. The stock fell 95 cents, or 1.9 percent, to 49 rand.  Sovereign Food Investments Ltd.  (SOV SJ): The chicken
producer said per-share earnings excluding one-time items is
expected to be between 80 percent and 100 percent lower in the
six months to end-August, compared to the corresponding period
the previous year, according to a stock exchange statement. The
Uitenhage-based company’s shares advanced 15 cents, or 2.7
percent, to 5.65 rand.  Shares or American depositary receipts of the following South
African companies closed as follows:  Anglo American Plc (AAUK US) rose 1.4 percent to $19.84.
AngloGold Ashanti Ltd. (AU US) added 1.1 percent to $44.07. BHP
Billiton Ltd. (BBL US) gained 1.7 percent to $61.80. DRDGold
Ltd. (DROOY US) dropped 2.2 percent to $5.01. Gold Fields Ltd.
(GFI US) rose 1.5 percent to $15.05. Harmony Gold Mining Co.
(HMY US) advanced 0.7 percent to $11.14. Impala Platinum
Holdings (IMPUY US) climbed 1.7 percent to $25.98. Sappi Ltd.
(SPP US) added 0.6 percent to $5.04. Sasol Ltd. (SSL US) rose
2.3 percent to $43.47.  To contact the reporter on this story:
 Garth Theunissen  in Johannesburg 
 gtheunissen@bloomberg.net  